CoastGIS '95:
INTERNATIONAL SYMPOSIUM ON GIS
AND COMPUTER MAPPING FOR COASTAL
ZONE MANAGEMENT.
University College, Cork, Ireland
February 3rd - 5th 1995

Introduction

The development and implementation of integrated
coastal management policies is now an established and
internationally-recognised ideal. However,  the tools and
methodologies for achieving such goals are still very much
under development. It is clear,  that for any management
of the shore to be effective, it is necessary for the policies
to be based on informed decision-making. This in turn
requires ready access to appropriate, reliable and timely
data and information, in suitable form for the task at hand.
Since much of this information and data is likely to have a
spatial component, computer mapping and geographical
information systems (GIS) offer great potential as tools for
assisting in sound coastal zone decision-making.

Examination of the literature relating to information
processing, as well as that from the coastal sciences,
reveals a paradox: on the one hand, there is clearly an
interest in, and a demand for, automated tools to assist in
processing coastal data; and yet many difficulties and
impediments remain before operational GIS are used as a
matter of routine for coastal management. However, there
is no doubt that GIS is rapidly becoming a major force in
natural and human resource management in general, and
specifically in the management of the coastal zone.

In recognition of these trends, the Commission on Coastal
Systems of the International Geographical Union, and the
Working Group on Marine and Coastal Mapping of the
International Cartographic Association invite you to
participate in an International Symposium on
Geographical Information Systems and Computer
Mapping for Coastal Zone Management, to be held at
University College Cork, Cork, Ireland.

The location

Cork is the second city of the Republic of Ireland. Cork is
an ideal venue for the Symposium: Cork City is situated at
the head of Cork Harbour, one of the largest natural
harbours in the world, and is easilly accessible from most
parts of the world thanks to good air and sea connections.

In 1995, University College Cork celebrates the 150th
Anniversary of its charter. The Department of Geography
of the College, in association with the Coastal Resources
Centre, is delighted to play host to the Symposium as part
of the official "UCC 150" activities.

The Symposium will take place within the central campus
of the university. Full audio-visual support, including
BARCO projector for computer output to screen, should
be available for presentations and demonstrations.

